SIMPLE: incantation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Incantation
<hw>In`can*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>incantatio</ets>, fr. <ets>incantare</ets> to chant a magic formula
over one: cf. F. <ets>incantation</ets>. See
<er>Enchant</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or process of using formulas sung or spoken,
with occult ceremonies, for the purpose of raising spirits, producing
enchantment, or affecting other magical results; enchantment.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Mysterious ceremony and <xex>incantation</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Burke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A formula of words used as above.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The repetitive invoking of old sayings, or emitting
a wordy discourse with little or no meaning, to avoid serious
discussion; obfuscation; <as>as, to defend one's views with empty
<ex>incantations</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incantatory</ent>⟦br⟧
